            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Miller\u2019s life is built on a foundation of practicality, a trait inherited from his father, a union mechanic in San Leandro. Growing up in the East Bay, Mark learned early on that value came from what you could fix with your own two hands. College was a distant concept, eclipsed by the immediate need to earn a living after high school. He started in the late '80s doing maintenance work for a small property management firm, learning plumbing, electrical, and HVAC systems not in a classroom, but in the basements and crawlspaces of aging buildings.\n\nHis career was a slow, steady climb. Mark was reliable and had a knack for seeing problems before they became disasters. In the mid-90s, he landed a job as a facilities technician at a downtown law firm, his first real taste of corporate San Francisco. While lawyers and paralegals debated cases, Mark ensured the lights stayed on and the air conditioning hummed. His steady competence saw him promoted to coordinator, then manager. He survived two office relocations and a major merger, each time proving himself indispensable. Now, as Senior Facilities Manager for a biotech research company, he oversees a complex infrastructure he understands better than anyone, a quiet master of a world unseen by the scientists he supports.\n\nMark\u2019s personal life has been similarly understated. A serious relationship ended in his late thirties, the gap between his practical world and his partner's academic one proving too wide to bridge. He never remarried, channeling his energy into his work and his rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, his home for over twenty years.\n\nHis daily routine is a metronome. The 6:15 AM N Judah train, the walk through SoMa, the checklists and contractor calls, and the ride home. He\u2019s a fixture at his neighborhood pub, where he\u2019ll have one beer and watch the Giants game. He\u2019s seen San Francisco transform, grumbling about the changes but feeling a deep, unshakeable connection to the fog-laced streets. His dream isn\u2019t grand; it\u2019s to save enough to buy a small, quiet place in Sonoma County. Until then, he finds satisfaction in a well-maintained building and the quiet hum of a city he helps keep running."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the deep, guttural roar of the '89 quake, the whole world groaning. While others ran into the street, his first instinct, born of his father's teaching, was to go down. In the shaking, dusty basement of a North Beach apartment building, he found the gas main and wrenched it shut with his own hands. It wasn't about being a hero; it was about seeing a problem and fixing it. In that chaotic moment, he found a profound sense of purpose that would guide his entire life.\n\n***\n\n2.\nHe recalls the night the power failed at the downtown law firm, just before a massive case filing. Suits were panicking, but Mark was in the sub-basement with a flashlight between his teeth, tracing schematics he\u2019d memorized. He located the faulty transfer switch and jury-rigged a bypass, restoring power to the critical floors. No one thanked him directly, but walking home past the glowing office windows, he felt a quiet, satisfying power. They were the brains, but he was the heartbeat they couldn't function without.\n\n***\n\n3.\nHe remembers the exact moment his most serious relationship ended, not with a fight, but over coffee. His girlfriend, a grad student, was talking passionately about post-structuralism, her eyes alive with theory. Mark just nodded, his mind trying to solve a persistent leak in a building\u2019s HVAC system. He saw the gulf between them then\u2014a chasm he couldn\u2019t bridge with a wrench or a plan. It was a quiet, lonely acceptance that he was built for a different, more tangible world.\n\n***\n\n4.\nHe remembers the first night in his Inner Richmond apartment, over twenty years ago. Sitting on the floor with a warm beer, the city\u2019s tech boom raging outside his window felt a million miles away. He heard the low moan of a foghorn and the familiar clatter of the N Judah rounding the corner. It wasn\u2019t just an apartment; it was an anchor. This small, rent-controlled space was his fortress against the frantic changes, the one part of San Francisco that would remain steadily his.\n\n***\n\n5.\nHe recalls the day the alarms shrieked in the biotech labs. A proprietary cooling unit for a million-dollar cell culture experiment had failed. The PhDs were frantic. Mark calmly diagnosed the cascading relay failure in the complex German system, bypassed the fault, and brought it back online using a part he\u2019d salvaged years earlier. In the scientists' stunned silence, he felt the full weight of his quiet mastery. They could map a genome, but he was the one who kept their world from melting."
